\title{"sora"}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Use when the user asks to generate, remix, poll, list, download, or delete Sora videos via OpenAI\u2019s video API using the bundled CLI (`scripts/sora.py`), including requests like \u201cgenerate AI video,\u201d \u201cSora,\u201d \u201cvideo remix,\u201d \u201cdownload video/thumbnail/spritesheet,\u201d and batch video generation; requires `OPENAI_API_KEY` and Sora API access."}

\subtree{
\title{Sora Video Generation Skill}
\p{Creates or manages short video clips for the current project (product demos, marketing spots, cinematic shots, UI mocks). Defaults to \code{\startverb sora-2\stopverb} and a structured prompt augmentation workflow, and prefers the bundled CLI for deterministic runs. Note: \code{\startverb $sora\stopverb} is a skill tag in prompts, not a shell command.}

\subtree{
\title{When to use}
\ul{
\li{Generate a new video clip from a prompt}
\li{Remix an existing video by ID}
\li{Poll status, list jobs, or download assets (video/thumbnail/spritesheet)}
\li{Batch runs (many prompts or variants)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Decision tree (create vs remix vs status/download vs batch)}
\ul{
\li{If the user has a \strong{video id} and wants a change → \strong{remix}}
\li{If the user has a \strong{video id} and wants status or assets → \strong{status/poll/download}}
\li{If the user needs many prompts/assets → \strong{create-batch}}
\li{If the user asks for two versions with a small change (same shot, different subject/detail) → \strong{create} the base, then \strong{remix} for the variation}
\li{Otherwise → \strong{create} (or \strong{create-and-poll} if they need a ready asset in one step)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Decide intent: create vs remix vs status/download vs batch.}
\li{Collect inputs: prompt, model, size, seconds, and any input reference image.}
\li{If batch: write a temporary JSONL under tmp/ (one job per line), run once, then delete the JSONL.}
\li{Prefer CLI augmentation flags (\code{\startverb --use-case\stopverb}, \code{\startverb --scene\stopverb}, \code{\startverb --camera\stopverb}, etc.) instead of pre-writing a structured prompt. If you already produced a structured prompt file, pass \code{\startverb --no-augment\stopverb} to avoid double-wrapping.}
\li{Run the bundled CLI (\code{\startverb scripts/sora.py\stopverb}) with sensible defaults (see references/cli.md). For long prompts, prefer \code{\startverb --prompt-file\stopverb} to avoid shell-escaping issues; pair with \code{\startverb --no-augment\stopverb} if the prompt is already structured.}
\li{For async jobs, poll until complete (or use create-and-poll).}
\li{Download assets (video/thumbnail/spritesheet) and save locally.}
\li{Remove intermediate files created during invocation (for example \code{\startverb prompt.txt\stopverb}, \code{\startverb remix_job.json\stopverb}, temp JSONL). If the sandbox blocks \code{\startverb rm\stopverb}, skip cleanup or truncate the files without surfacing an error.}
\li{Iterate with a single targeted change per prompt.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Authentication}
\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb OPENAI_API_KEY\stopverb} must be set for live API calls.}
}

\p{If the key is missing, give the user these steps:}

\ol{
\li{Create an API key in the OpenAI platform UI: https://platform.openai.com/api-keys}
\li{Set \code{\startverb OPENAI_API_KEY\stopverb} as an environment variable in their system.}
\li{Offer to guide them through setting the environment variable for their OS/shell if needed.}
}

\ul{
\li{Never ask the user to paste the full key in chat. Ask them to set it locally and confirm when ready.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Defaults & rules}
\ul{
\li{Default model: \code{\startverb sora-2\stopverb} (use \code{\startverb sora-2-pro\stopverb} for higher fidelity).}
\li{Default size: \code{\startverb 1280x720\stopverb}.}
\li{Default seconds: \code{\startverb 4\stopverb} (allowed: "4", "8", "12" as strings).}
\li{Always set size and seconds via API params; prose will not change them.}
\li{Use the OpenAI Python SDK (\code{\startverb openai\stopverb} package); do not use raw HTTP.}
\li{Require \code{\startverb OPENAI_API_KEY\stopverb} before any live API call.}
\li{If uv cache permissions fail, set \code{\startverb UV_CACHE_DIR=/tmp/uv-cache\stopverb}.}
\li{Input reference images must be jpg/png/webp and should match target size.}
\li{Download URLs expire after about 1 hour; copy assets to your own storage.}
\li{Prefer the bundled CLI and \strong{never modify} \code{\startverb scripts/sora.py\stopverb} unless the user asks.}
\li{Sora can generate audio; if a user requests voiceover/audio, specify it explicitly in the \code{\startverb Audio:\stopverb} and \code{\startverb Dialogue:\stopverb} lines and keep it short.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{API limitations}
\ul{
\li{Models are limited to \code{\startverb sora-2\stopverb} and \code{\startverb sora-2-pro\stopverb}.}
\li{API access to Sora models requires an organization-verified account.}
\li{Duration is limited to 4/8/12 seconds and must be set via the \code{\startverb seconds\stopverb} parameter.}
\li{The API expects \code{\startverb seconds\stopverb} as a string enum ("4", "8", "12").}
\li{Output sizes are limited by model (see \code{\startverb references/video-api.md\stopverb} for the supported sizes).}
\li{Video creation is async; you must poll for completion before downloading.}
\li{Rate limits apply by usage tier (do not list specific limits).}
\li{Content restrictions are enforced by the API (see Guardrails below).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Guardrails (must enforce)}
\ul{
\li{Only content suitable for audiences under 18.}
\li{No copyrighted characters or copyrighted music.}
\li{No real people (including public figures).}
\li{Input images with human faces are rejected.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prompt augmentation}
\p{Reformat prompts into a structured, production-oriented spec. Only make implicit details explicit; do not invent new creative requirements.}

\p{Template (include only relevant lines):}

\pre{\startverb
Use case: <where the clip will be used>
Primary request: <user's main prompt>
Scene/background: <location, time of day, atmosphere>
Subject: <main subject>
Action: <single clear action>
Camera: <shot type, angle, motion>
Lighting/mood: <lighting + mood>
Color palette: <3-5 color anchors>
Style/format: <film/animation/format cues>
Timing/beats: <counts or beats>
Audio: <ambient cue / music / voiceover if requested>
Text (verbatim): "<exact text>"
Dialogue:
<dialogue>
- Speaker: "Short line."
</dialogue>
Constraints: <must keep/must avoid>
Avoid: <negative constraints>
\stopverb}

\p{Augmentation rules:}

\ul{
\li{Keep it short; add only details the user already implied or provided elsewhere.}
\li{For remixes, explicitly list invariants ("same shot, change only X").}
\li{If any critical detail is missing and blocks success, ask a question; otherwise proceed.}
\li{If you pass a structured prompt file to the CLI, add \code{\startverb --no-augment\stopverb} to avoid the tool re-wrapping it.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Generation example (single shot)}
\pre{\startverb
Use case: product teaser
Primary request: a close-up of a matte black camera on a pedestal
Action: slow 30-degree orbit over 4 seconds
Camera: 85mm, shallow depth of field, gentle handheld drift
Lighting/mood: soft key light, subtle rim, premium studio feel
Constraints: no logos, no text
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Remix example (invariants)}
\pre{\startverb
Primary request: same shot and framing, switch palette to teal/sand/rust with warmer backlight
Constraints: keep the subject and camera move unchanged
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prompting best practices (short list)}
\ul{
\li{One main action + one camera move per shot.}
\li{Use counts or beats for timing ("two steps, pause, turn").}
\li{Keep text short and the camera locked-off for UI or on-screen text.}
\li{Add a brief avoid line when artifacts appear (flicker, jitter, fast motion).}
\li{Shorter prompts are more creative; longer prompts are more controlled.}
\li{Put dialogue in a dedicated block; keep lines short for 4-8s clips.}
\li{State invariants explicitly for remixes (same shot, same camera move).}
\li{Iterate with single-change follow-ups to preserve continuity.}
}
}

